The government wants to limit the torture of "witches", as published in a pamphlet
Women considered witches in Burkina Faso share certain characteristics.
They are usually of advanced age, cannot work, for example, for health reasons, are single and have no children.
Women who "return" witches are sent to an isolated area, so that they do not harm the rest of the village.
"Men seldom suffer such a thing if not."
“Healthy young women are also not isolated, because they help in the labors and have children,” explains a nun who, in the capital of the West African state of Burkina Faso, takes care of a special residence of more than 100 women expelled from their communities.
The local government has decided to oppose this unusual "social measure".
He issued an informative pamphlet that should help prevent the witch hunt.
However, this has a catch.
“More than 70% of adults in Burkina Faso cannot read,” warns Die Standard newspaper about the disadvantages of written awareness.
Accusations of witchcraft are also common in other African countries.
In Ghana, Burkina Faso’s neighbor, 72-year-old Ammy Hemmah died last week when three women and two men tortured her, covered her with gasoline and burned her.
The news appeared on the BBC.
The authors claim that it was due to a miserable pile of circumstances.
According to her version, the woman was caught in the oil used for ritual anointings.
It caught fire when the group wanted to "throw out the evil spirits" of the woman.
The isolation of "witches" is supported by people of all educational levels.
The newspaper Der Standard quoted a 42-year-old businessman from Burkina Faso as saying: “The soul-eaters have always been a danger,” he said.
While in Burkina Faso the government tries to appease the witch hunt, in Gambia last year the president still participated in it.
"The Gambian president Jammeh, after the death of his aunt, launched a wide-ranging witch hunt that allegedly had been related to his death and had attempted to kill the president himself by black magic."
“To help him, he brought shamans from nearby Guinea who, protected by police, the military and the president’s personal escort, forcibly took randomly selected men and women from Gambian villages to the president’s property in Kanilai,” Amnesty International said in its report.
On the farm, the arrested people had to drink a potion of herbs with hallucinogenic effects that, in addition, caused intestinal and kidney problems.
Two of those arrested did not survive the stay on the estate.
Following international pressure, they finally released about 1,000 detainees.
The tenant of Bakala: warms up with charcoal stoves and signs a higher rent
The elderly and stiff man crossed the doors of the customer service center of the RPG company Byty of the "coal magnate" Zde<0xC5><0x88>ek Bakala, the largest private owner of flats for rent in the Czech Republic.
Under his arm he carried documents with the new three-story leases: his own, his daughter’s and his son’s, who is serving his sentence.
The three of them have just been caught up in the liberalization of rents.
Instead of 3,500 Czech crowns per month, the child will pay from next year 4,100 crowns for a two-room apartment with a separate second-class kitchen.
"In addition, it does not have hot water and the heating is based on a solid fuel boiler," shows with the finger the man in the new contract of his son, on whose signature he has full powers.
“But I signed it,” he explains half angry, half resigned.
The civil association BytyOKD.cz, which called the new rental conditions "incorrect and indecent", recommends that tenants not sign the new contracts and wait until December 7, when it will publish a guide informing how to proceed in these cases.
But, in view of this, the man only makes an ademan.
“Everyone says one thing,” he says with a bad face.
Ostrava is becoming a major testing ground for liberalization.
After the New Year will happen with the vast majority of the apartments that, in the Czech Republic, were so far under a regulated rent.
Therefore, Aktu<0xC3><0xA1>ln<0xC4><0x9B>.cz decided to visit the "laboratory" in person.
The RPG mining waiting room is one of four in Ostrava and, on Tuesday at nine, it was already full.
Right next to the doors are the security guards and next to them a machine to pick up a number.
"Rent 2011", can be read on a light button on your touch screen.
When you press it, a piece of paper with a number comes out of the machine.
There is almost no time to read "157" and the number already appears on the large screen located at the top of the room.
In a second, you're in line.
Soon after, an elderly married couple arrives to ask, but the crowd in the room is not here for the new rentals.
Most people come to solve common problems, as in the past: requests for arrangements, insurance issues and similar matters.
The letters with the new rental contracts will arrive in Ostrava to the mailboxes of tenants of most of the 44,000 RPG-owned flats around mid-November.
RPG Byty proposes in the cards an increase of the rent between 15 and 38%.
On November 18, a special window opens in the customer service center for new rentals.
“It’s been running for a week, so it’s starting,” the workers respond, after hesitating briefly, when the client introduces himself as a journalist.
Liberalization and Bakala’s old mining flats are the most sensitive issues in the area.
Before the elections, they were treated loud and clear by the deputy speaker of the parliament, Lubom<0xC3><0xAD>r Zaor<0xC3><0xA1>lek, from Ostrava, of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSD, and now appear continuously in the newspapers of the area.
"Twenty years later I want a new floor."
“They didn’t even change my goddamn bathroom plate,” the man mentioned in the introduction vents.
According to the workers, at the moment they come more than anything retired to check if they receive a discount on the rent if they sign in time, as promised by the special offer of RPG.
The remaining tenants who sign the new contract before December 15 will also receive half of the discount on the February rental.
However, the window of mining “liberalization” certainly fails to dispel the avalanche of doubts.
"Of the 360 customers who were here yesterday, they only asked about the rental in 2011 about forty or fifty people," estimates the employee of the window.
Meanwhile, RPG proposes on the web and on its boards to hold individual meetings on contracts when necessary.
If the two parties do not reach an agreement on the rent, the matter will have to be resolved by an independent judge.
"This is not a threat, but information about the only possible way to proceed and fully compliant with the law," RPG warns on its pages.
“No one is going to be judged here,” says one of RPG Byty’s employees, and a man standing on the street in front of the customer service center gives her, at least in part, the reason.
“I get a pension of 13,000 and I have 5,000 left for food; I have no means to go to court,” he says.
But immediately, the employee sows doubt.
"We'll see."
"Mr. Zaor<0xC3><0xA1>lek warns you in the media not to sign, so maybe people will wait," he said.
The rent regulation will cease to exist in most of the Czech Republic in early 2011 and, according to RPG Byty, its increase is an economic necessity.
“Current rentals still do not cover even the amounts needed to maintain the community fund,” recalls Pavel Klime<0xC5><0xA1>, director of the residential portfolio of the RPG company Byty, adding that the neglected state of the community fund that angers tenants is, for landlords, the main reason for increasing rent.
While in the five years between 2005 and 2010, RPG was able to invest four billion dollars in apartments, in the four years from 2011 to 2014, the figure will increase to 5.2 billion.
The large screen hanging from the ceiling, in front of the waiting room seats, now repeats some data that stand out in red.
"The increase in rent in 2011 by 15% and less applies to 31,200 apartments, i.e. more than 90% of RPG properties."
"In addition, it will always be at most 7.50 Czech kroner per square meter per month," it says on the screen.
Just increased by 38% the rent of 400 floors of the RPG portfolio.
“In such cases, this is an increase from extremely low amounts, of 19.66 crowns per square meter,” says RPG.
At 2,600 flats, rent will remain unchanged next year.
RPG Byty promises that liberalization will not suddenly affect rents, but will escalate in four to eight years.
In addition, he adds the following commitment: the company will invest all the money from the rent increase (see the graph) again in the floors, mainly in savings in heating: new windows and heating.
Priority will be given to those who sign the lease agreement.
Architects have understood that offices also need daycare
The Avriopoint administrative building in Brno is the new headquarters of the company Arch.Design.
No one would say that it also hides inside a small nursery with everything that belongs to such facilities: colorful walls, creative furniture and even a miniature park on the outdoor terrace.
Since October last year, the children of Arch.Design employees can attend.
The architectural project company Arch.Design, from whose study numerous well-known buildings emerged from Brno, thought from the first sketches of the Avriopoint building to include a space for its mini-kindergarten.
About 90 people work in the company, mainly in the age of the baby boom and wanted to allow architects and designers to return to work soon after maternity.
Along with the possibility of enjoying a reduced schedule, the daycare is one of the benefits that Arch.Design offers its workers as part of its social program.
Builders and architects in this way have the possibility to combine a demanding profession with the care of children.
The mini-kindergarten was an idea of Arch.Designu’s own employees and, with the support of management, they managed to obtain funding from the European Union and the Ministry of Labour and Social Affairs.
The company's mini-nursery is financed through the European Social Fund under the Human Resources and Employment Operational Programme, as well as the state budget of the Czech Republic.
Thanks to the funding granted (more than CZK 2.8 million) they were able to purchase the equipment and, after two years, hire qualified personnel and services.
When funding is exhausted (two years), Arch.Design has the obligation to keep the mini-kindergarten in operation with its own funds for three years.
The preparation of the project lasted one year and the submission of the application for funding contributed the company Economy Rating.
The care of the children is in the hands of qualified staff, and a nurse and a teacher from the Ministry of Education are present throughout the day for their care. The nursery currently welcomes children without age limit, although most of them are under three years old.
Since it is a "mini-kindergarten", it can only accommodate a maximum of five children simultaneously, although with shifts they come more during the day.
The operation of the nursery is flexible to suit the needs of the parents and the children of all workers have the same right to use the nursery, regardless of the hierarchy within the company.
Although it is an individual education and care, the contents of the mini-kindergarten programme are comparable to the regular pre-school programme.
In it children not only play, but also receive quality teaching: from basic learning to school preparation, they teach even English.
The classroom not only has toys and board games, but also a computer for children.
The presence of young children in the company itself create a friendly and positive environment.
Parents can go to see their children at any time and avoid the stress of picking up late school children when they are away from their workplace.
Thus, parents are more productive while working.
It is not surprising that this naturally generates a loyalty relationship between the worker and his employer.
In this way, Arch.Design ranks among the firms that offer a great advantage for the admission of new workers: they support the family and, ultimately, this program reinforced the marketing of staff.
The House of Bones continues to fascinate after 100 years. Look at Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s interiors
The roof looks like the back of a prehistoric lizard, the stairs resemble the column of a dinosaur and the balconies look like the mouth of an open fish.
This is the Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, in Barcelona, by the Catalan architect Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Due to its skeleton-like shape, the locals nicknamed it "the house of bones".
Its organic forms, its striking colors, the novel use of stone, the fragments of tiles and mosaics, a facade reminiscent of scales and the ubiquitous lines gently curved, all this is typical of the secession of Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
The cover of the house plays with dreamlike lines, delicate colors and textures taken from nature and fauna.
Paying more attention, you observe a certain geometry, rhythm and a carefully thought out order.
At night, the entire fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house looks even more impressive, since it is illuminated in such a way that the brightness of the colors is improved.
Snake and the twisting of the shapes continues to surprise us also inside.
Corrugated wood copies window frames, railings, door ornaments, peepholes and signs.
Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, located in the Eixample district at number 43 of the lively shopping street of Passeig de Gr<0xC3><0xA0>cia, emerged from the remodeling of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortés.
The reconstruction took two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, the wealthy industrialist Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, initially insisted on tearing down the previous building and starting from scratch, but soon accepted Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s idea of carrying out a novel and cheaper reconstruction.
However, Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, made up of several apartments, was not designed by Antoni Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> alone.
The architect Josep Mar<0xC3><0xAD>a Jujol collaborated in the design.
In fact, in his plans of the project appeared ornaments for the representative apartment of the owner of the property and the mosaics used in the facade.
In the fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade also workers other creators and artists.
The collaboration in the proposals of Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3> was the beginning of Jujol’s successful collaboration with Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>.
Jujol participated in the construction of Casa Mil<0xC3><0xA1> and Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>’s Park Güell, where other pieces of it are located.
Due to its organic form, the locals shortly after its completion dubbed it "the house of bones".
Others, due to the specific opening mechanism of the windows, began to call it "the house of yawning".
It is also said that, at the top of the construction, appears the sword of St. George, patron saint of Catalonia.
Other sculptural elements of the construction hide religious motives.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> designed in the house a unique system for the time of central heating with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Its inclination of forty-five degrees may be strange.
During the construction, Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> did not respect at all the construction rules of the moment and was not influenced by them.
Even so, the construction obtained the corresponding permission from the beginning, although evidently in it the data indicated about the planned reconstruction were so vague that, two years later, at its completion, the city was so impacted by the result that it asked to be corrected.
It bothered him, for example, that the construction included columns even to the public sidewalk.
The arrangements were never made, rather the opposite: just fifteen days after the request of the city council, Josep Batll<0xC3><0xB3> requested (and obtained) permission to rent the two highest floors of the building.
On the lower floors the owner himself was installed.
In the gallery on the second floor was the living room and on the third floor the bedrooms and the private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The six-story house is completely traversed by a staircase leading to the roof terrace.
The basic elements of the reform consisted of breaking all angles and straight lines, covering them with curved walls.
Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> also worked with the modern concept of space connection.
The common part can be connected completely by opening the doors of the salons and a larger group can communicate in this way without problems, without giving up the privacy necessary for more intimate conversations.
The house, with the reconstruction of Gaud<0xC3><0xAD>, not only obtained a new facade, but also an unusual roof and two additional floors.
It is also impressive how Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> plays with light, white and blue tiles covering the inner courtyard and skylights.
The play with the two colors brings maximum light on all floors of the house.
It was simply based on the principle that white reflects more light than dark colors, which instead absorb the sun’s rays.
Anyone can visit Casa Batll<0xC3><0xB3>, which in 2005 was added to the UNESCO World Heritage List.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious apartment and the most recharged of those accessible to the public.
The owners decided to open the doors to the public in 2002, on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
With the visits they confirmed, or discovered, that it is a very beneficial business and expanded the visits to the common area and the attic, including the roof terrace.
The price of the entrance to the monument is not negligible, it reaches 16.50 euros, although students, retirees and holders of tourist cards get a 20% discount.
The amount considerably exceeds the price of the entrance of other Gaud<0xC3><0xAD> constructions in the city.
