Defense Ministry spokesman Jan Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek defends the hundreds of kilometers of wick, saying he will also have stockpiles of this "munition" for at least ten years.
However, Jan D<0xC4><0x9B>ck<0xC3><0xBD>, of STV Group, indicates that the wick only has a shelf life of four years and, in the case of pyrotechnic products for the army or the police, of two years.
"If stored in perfect conditions, it can last up to four," says one of the soldiers who, due to possible criticism from the army, does not want to give his name.
After the end of its useful life, each ammunition must be carefully checked to see if it remains reliable and will not harm soldiers.
But these tests are not free and require additional investment.
Another argument of the Ministry is that, by buying 445 kilometers of wick, he obtained a discount.
"They cost us 60 percent less than last year's order of 244 kilometers," said Pej<0xC5><0xA1>ek, a spokesman for the Ministry of Defence's shopping centre.
Just to compare: the annual wick consumption of the police pyrotechnics, which eliminate the ammunition of World War II or left by the Soviet army, has not exceeded 1,500 meters for years.
In addition, the police always ask only the right amount to exhaust the ammunition before its useful life runs out.
They decided it for safety reasons for pyrotechnicians and, in the meantime, more modern and reliable wick types can be obtained.
The Ministry is already clearly struggling to finish tens of thousands of tons of ammunition from the time of the Warsaw Pact, when the Czechoslovak army of 200,000 people was preparing for a campaign in the Rhine.
According to the pyrotechnics with whom MF DNES spoke, after a couple of years there will be the following problem with the current one: you will have to remove hundreds of kilometers of old wick, which is now being bought "cheap".
