An arsenic-resistant microbe raises the possibility of new life forms on Earth... or elsewhere
The discovery of a strange bacterium that can use arsenic as one of its nutrients expands the possibility of finding new life forms on Earth and possibly other planets.
Although the researchers discovered the curious bacteria here on Earth, they say it shows that there may be life forms without the main elements they considered essential.
"This body has a double capacity."
"It can grow either with phosphorus or with arsenic."
"That makes it a very peculiar thing, although it's not far from being a really 'alien' type of life form," said Paul C. W. Davies of Arizona State University, co-author of the report appearing in Thursday's online edition of the journal Science.
It has long been considered that there are six major elements essential to life: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus and sulfur.
However, researchers have found that the bacteria, found in Mono Lake, California, may continue to grow after replacing phosphorus with arsenic.
“It makes you wonder what else is possible,” said Ariel D. Anbar of Arizona State University, co-author of the report.
According to Anbar, the finding is important for the search for life on different planets of Earth, since researchers need to be able to recognize life, to know how it looks.
The study focuses on a microbe discovered on Earth.
However, the convening of a press conference to discuss it, in which no details of the discovery were disclosed, generated great speculation on the Internet about the possibility that the report indicated the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
He didn't.
What the discovery “shows is that in other planetary environments, there may be organisms that use other elements to drive their biochemistry and that the set of “standard” elements we consider indispensable for life may not be as fixed,” said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Planetary and Space Sciences Research Institute, Open University, in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the investigation team.
"This work is novel because it demonstrates the substitution of one element for another in biochemistry and basic biochemical structure," added Cockell.
The discovery was not by chance.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of NASA's astrobiology institute, who led the study, focused on Mono Lake because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are similar from a chemical point of view, so he speculated that a microbe exposed to both could replace one with the other.
“Arsenic is toxic mainly because its chemical behavior is similar to that of phosphorus.”
“Therefore, it can be difficult for organisms to differentiate them.”
“However, arsenic is different enough that it doesn’t work as well as phosphorus, so it comes in and, so to speak, it crams the biochemical machinery,” Anbar explains.
The researchers collected the bacteria known as GFAJ-1 and exposed them to ever-increasing concentrations of arsenic, which they were able to adapt to and use to grow.
The microbe grows best with phosphorus, but demonstrating that it can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that an arsenic-using form of life may naturally exist, either in other areas of the Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is more common.
Jamie S. Foster, assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said the idea that arsenic can be replaced by phosphorus is not new, but an example to prove that it works had never been found.
Arsenic was more common in the early ages of Earth, he said, so researchers speculated that early life forms may have used it.
“It does suggest that there might be other means of generating life, not just the way life formed on Earth in ancient times,” said Foster, who was not part of Wolfe-Simon’s research team.
The research was supported by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institutes of Health.
