Tech Toys wants to keep the balance of its gift budget
While the iPad is the top contender for being this year’s most wonderful toy, followed by, perhaps, the Microsoft Kinect video game system, both can mean a significant nick in your gift budget.
Consider that for the price of an iPad you can buy five BMX bikes for $99 each, and a Kinect game costs the same as 10 classic jump ropes adorned with beads, or about 48 cans of the Play-Doh.
But there are ways to keep your gift budget in balance.
I recently visited three national toy sellers, Wal-Mart, Toys "R" Us and BJ's Wholesale Club, to see what electronic toys they could buy for under $80.
It was immediately clear that Moore’s Law has been working; this year’s tech toy will likely have more power, costing the same and even slightly less compared to last year’s.
Also, while there are generally fewer new toys with associated websites, two of the best-known of their kind, Webkinz and Club Penguin, have more offers.
And toys powered by button batteries are on the rise, as are toys with rechargeable batteries.
Here are some recommendations.
(All prices are from Toys "R" Us, unless otherwise noted).
The Sing-a-ma-jigs (Mattel, $13, for 3 years and more) are guinea pig-sized stuffed toys that sing a note when their bellies are squeezed.
One squeeze equals one note, and a second squeeze begins to assemble a song.
If you buy more than one, they will sing in harmony.
Caution: Once you start to squeeze, you can’t stop.
For singing combined with dancing, Dance Star Mickey (Fisher-Price, $60, for 2 years and more) is the best option.
Borrowing from last year’s Elmo Live technology, the 14-inch animatronic doll plays shift-shifting games like Sim<0xC3><0xB3>n Dice, and can make the lunar leap, thanks to its innovative wheeled articulated feet with locking device.
The children who tested the toy used Mickey as a dance instructor, although his parents complained about the lack of a volume control.
If you're a kid from the '80s, you can remember Alphie, one of the first computerized educational toys.
He is back (Hasbro/Playskool, $40, for 3 years and more), with a backpack full of question letters designed to turn a car ride into a session with an intriguing self-correcting exercise booklet.
If you are wary of giving your child your smartphone, here are three independent alternatives.
VTech’s MobiGo ($60, ages 3 to 8) is the cheapest and easiest to use, featuring a qwerty keyboard; although the games don’t teach as effectively as the Leapster Explorer ($70, ages 3 to 12), it’s the first major set-up of the Leapster line, with a newer, brighter display.
No version is compatible with old cartridges.
Fisher-Price’s iXL ($90, ages 3 to 7) uses an iTunes-like system to present games and e-books, and has an SD card slot for viewing family photos.
Finally, Scrabble Flash ($30, Hasbro, for 8 years and up) is a set of five blocks just larger than a matchbox, each with its own LED display.
The goal is to assemble words by placing the blocks in a row before time runs out; it’s formidable for an improvised word-assembly competition.
More and more toys have some kind of online connection.
Based only on their presence in toy stores, the two largest are Webkinz and Club Penguin.
