2013 will mean the birth of a new currency area, in which offending countries will be severely sanctioned, may be forced to declare themselves in default and, in that case, the private sector will also bear part of the cost.
Germany is pointing out that we must follow a severe growth path with high savings and investment rates, moderation in consumption, improvements in productivity and competitiveness, and positive external balances.
Another debt- and construction-based alternative, with huge gaps in the balance of payments, like the one that presided over Spanish growth in the boom years, is simply not going to be tolerated.
The invitation is clear.
And it would be wrong for us not to understand it.
It is not just about reducing the public deficit to 3% in 2013.
What they demand of us is much harder.
And the worst thing we could do in these circumstances is to deceive ourselves.
I hope that the current turbulence will give way to greater tranquility.
And that we take advantage of the window of opportunity that we have been given, until the spring of 2013.
It seems that President Zapatero has also understood this and his double manifesto (the reforms promised after last Saturday's meeting with big companies and yesterday's announcement of new measures) suggests that, despite criticism of Merkel, the thesis that we must put order at home has been paved the way.
But the red line that Germany has drawn there is, and it doesn’t seem to be moving it.
And, among the possibilities that are contemplated, that of leaving a monetary zone too crowded with low-income countries, can not be excluded.
Then Germany will always be able to tell us that it had already warned us.
Sport and Law Fraud
Tricks like those of Alonso and Ramos against Ajax demonstrate ingenuity but not willingness to escape a sanction.
The expulsion allegedly by two Real Madrid players (Xabi Alonso and Sergio Ramos) in the November 23 Champions League match against Ajax has prompted ink to be written about whether or not such behavior is unsportsmanlike and whether, eventually, both players should be sanctioned by UEFA.
As is well known, in the absence of a few minutes to finish the game (which their team already clearly had won), the two players deliberately lost time in drawing faults to cause the referee to show them the second yellow card.
That way, and since Real Madrid will end up as the leader of their group, both players will comply with the regulatory sanction the next match of the league, against Auxerre, and can pass clean of cards to the next phase.
Finally, the UEFA discipline committee has sanctioned the team’s coach, José Mourinho, with two matches and different financial amounts for the players involved.
Provoking a yellow card in circumstances like this or similar is not a new practice, but rather frequent in the world of football.
It is so widespread that it is part of the ethos, of the unwritten rules, but followed, of this sport.
Part of the debate arising in the reported case is due to the fact that it has been starred by a team of the Real Madrid entity (which in its anthem boasts of nobility and honor, and that on past occasions has fined its players for similar acts) and to the orchestrated dramatization, apparently, by Mourinho, who adds another episode to his long history of histrionic and provocative technician.
In any case, the debate revolves around whether this type of behaviour not expressly prohibited by the regulation contradicts the principles of sport, that is, whether these actions commit fraud of law; in fact, they are actions respectful of the sporting regulation, but seem to evade its meaning.
The question is to examine the type of damage they cause to the sporting spirit.
One of the assets that comprises the sports spirit is the physical integrity of the opposing players, an aspect that with these actions was not put in danger, that is, there was no violent play.
Another of these goods that are alluded to with fair play is to prevent the team of the offending players from unfairly taking advantage of the opposing team, which also did not happen.
Now, the paradox of the action of Real Madrid players is that it did not accommodate what we normally characterize as cheating or fraud of law, because their violation of the rules was not done in secret to try to avoid the sanction, but precisely their action tried to be the most obvious to receive the punishment of the referee.
They waited and gladly accepted the sanction.
Another question is what kind of advantage do offenders gain in the intentional misconduct examined.
Here it seems necessary to verify that the opponent is not disadvantaged or profit is obtained in the same game, because obviously the result of the action means leaving the team with fewer players.
Nor is it a useful strategy for the next match, as the club will not be able to count on these players.
The advantage, of course, is that players will start the next phase of the Champions League without cards that could threaten their participation in a future match.
But it is a long-term advantage, with a certain degree of indeterminacy, as the team can be eliminated at the first change, and also with this performance the players fulfill a penalty game and move on to the second cycle of cards, in which the suspension for accumulation of cards occurs with one less than in the first cycle.
So, if you go through rounds, it is not so clear that it is an advantage.
In short, these actions do not go against the spirit of sport, of which it is part to make strategic decisions that favor making the most of what the rules allow.
In the case at hand, the players did not act to evade the application of the sanction (this would be a clear case of law fraud), but rather chose when to submit to it.
They made a strategic decision without circumventing the punishment or running away from it.
Although the border between ingenuity and fraud is blurred, this time I think it was a clear case of ingenuity.
The controversy, it seems to me, arises from two factors: because it was two self-expulsions and the way in which the transmission of the directive to provoke them was carried out.
The harm caused to the principles of sport by these actions is not as ethical as it is aesthetic.
