China maintains greenhouse gas reduction targets
The representative of that country at COP16 said that his country has made enormous efforts to reduce the carbon footprint and detailed that it supports its offer to reduce by 2020 between 40 and 45 percent of its greenhouse gas emissions.
China maintains its bid to reduce its greenhouse gas emissions by 40 to 45 percent by 2020, said Su Wei, the country’s representative at the COP16.
In his first public appearance at the 16th Conference of the Parties to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change (COP16), Su Wei said his country has made enormous efforts to reduce its carbon footprint and to reconvert its industry.
In fact, he said, his country has invested $245 million over the past four years in efforts to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.
However, he made it clear that China would not alter its objectives, but would continue to work together with the international community in that regard.
He noted that China’s climate change strategy is divided into four areas: dialogue; capacity building; institution building; and support for pilot programmes.
In all these areas, progress has been made, including the adoption last year of a new Energy Law, which includes the objectives set in terms of reducing gas emissions, he explained.
In China, federal authorities have been working in coordination with state and local authorities to achieve energy-saving, energy-efficient and emission-reducing goals.
In addition, several multi-year plans, both funded by the Chinese government and by governments of other countries, are underway or have already been completed.
For example, he referred to the Energy Efficiency Programme, which was implemented over the past five years and which received investments from the United Nations (UN), the government and the private sector.
A provincial climate change project is also underway, another for the change of incandescent spotlights by savers and another for mitigation and adaptation, he said.
At the same table, Martin Krol, the country’s government’s scientific advisor on climate change, said China’s efforts have been greater than generally thought.
For example, he explained, the per capita emission of greenhouse gases in China is six tons per person, while in the United States it is 100 tons; China is responsible for 9 percent of the historical contribution to pollution.
It has also made unprecedented efforts in energy use, such as increasing energy efficiency by 20 percent over the past five years and expects to do the same by 2020.
