U.S. Changes Rules for Obtaining a Visa
Individuals should go to the Visa Applicant Service Centers before their interview in the Consular Section; the cost will be lower and as well as the waiting time.
As of January 10, 2011, the procedure for processing a visa at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
Under the new procedure, most applicants will be required to go to Visa Applicant Service Centers (ASCs) before their Consular Section interview.
The ASC staff will take the applicant’s biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have certain advantages for applicants, including:
The total cost of processing the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to arrange the appointment, another payment to process the visa application and another one for the courier service to deliver the document.
The applicant will only make a one-time payment covering all three services.
The current fee will remain unchanged: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for petition visa cases (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for merchant and investor visas.
People who wish to renew their visa will not have to go to an interview with the Consular Officer, but will only go to the nearest ASC where they will present their documents and take their fingerprints.
Because the biometric information will be taken at the ASC, applicants who require a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will remain in this one less time than in the past.
Likewise, those who apply for a visa at the Consulates in Ciudad Juarez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the extra service fee of $26.
For further information on the new visa application procedure, please visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/bulletines/sp101201_Visa-FAQs.html
